Reasoning: The paper deals with a problem in spectral graph theory and its application to the Asymmetric Traveling Salesman Problem. The use of real stability of polynomials and the concept of isotropic position suggest that the paper may belong to the sub-categories of cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.IT (Information Theory). The application to the Asymmetric TSP suggests that the paper may also belong to the sub-categories of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.NA (Numerical Analysis). Finally, the use of probabilistic methods and the concept of strongly Rayleigh measures suggest that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
